    <item>
      <title>Fibonacci numbers</title>
      <link>https://aureooms.github.io/math/2015/06/29/fibonacci/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://aureooms.github.io/math/2015/06/29/fibonacci/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;The Fibonacci numbers are defined as &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(f_0 = 0,\ f_1 = 1\)&lt;/span&gt; and, for &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(i \ge
2,\ f_i = f_{i-1} + f_{i-2}\)&lt;/span&gt;. Here is the beginning of the Fibonacci sequence:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\[0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, 21, \ldots\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We generalize the definition above by changing the two initial values, for
example with &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(f_0 = 4,\ f_1 = 6\)&lt;/span&gt; we obtain&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\[4, 6, 10, 16, 26, 42, \ldots\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Inverse sum equations</title>
      <link>https://aureooms.github.io/math/2015/06/29/inverse-sum/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 29 Jun 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://aureooms.github.io/math/2015/06/29/inverse-sum/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;We are given &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(k &gt; 0 \in \mathbb{R}\)&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(a_1, a_2, \ldots, a_n \ge 1 \in \mathbb{N}\)&lt;/span&gt; such that&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\[
a_1 &lt; a_2 &lt; \cdots &lt; a_n.
\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We want to solve the following equation&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\[
\frac{1}{a_1} +
\frac{1}{a_2} +
\cdots +
\frac{1}{a_n} = k.
\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Binomial coefficient tricks</title>
      <link>https://aureooms.github.io/math/2015/06/24/binomial-coefficient-tricks/</link>
      <pubDate>Wed, 24 Jun 2015 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://aureooms.github.io/math/2015/06/24/binomial-coefficient-tricks/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\[
\binom{n}{k} = \binom{n}{n-k}
\]&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;holds because keeping &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(k\)&lt;/span&gt; elements from &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(n\)&lt;/span&gt; elements is equivalent
to discarding &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(n-k\)&lt;/span&gt; elements from &lt;span  class=&#34;math&#34;&gt;\(n\)&lt;/span&gt; elements.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    
